final_Adjusted_R.Squared <- Adjusted_R.Squared
avg.auto <- mean(data[data$am==0,"mpg"])
avg.manual <- mean(data[data$am==1,"mpg"])
@


\section*{Executive Summary}

The final regression model captured \Sexpr{round(table$r.squared*100,2)} percent of the total variance and \Sexpr{round(table$adj.r.squared*100,2)} percent of the adjusted variance. The coefficents indicate that when the weight of the vehicle increases by 1,000 lbs, the mpg decreases by \Sexpr{round(-t[2,1],3)} for cars with automatic transmissions, and decreases by \Sexpr{round(-t[3,1],3)} for cars with manual transmissions. When the quarter-mile performance time increases by 1 second, the mpg increases \Sexpr{round(t[4,1],3)} for cars with automatic transmissions and \Sexpr{round(t[5,1],3)} for cars with manual transmissions. The answer to the question of whether an automatic or manual transmission is better for MPG would depend on the particular vehicle. The heavier the vehicle, the greater the MPG penalty for having a manual transmission. The quicker the vehicle, the greater the MPG advantage for the manual transmission. The conclusion of this analysis in one sentence is that the MPG variable is largely influenced by the interaction between weight, acceleration and transmission type. T-Testing indicated that the mean difference in MPG between the two transmission types is \Sexpr{round(avg.manual - avg.auto,3)} 

