\section*{Conclusion}

The final model captures \Sexpr{round(table$r.squared*100,2)} percent of the total variance and
\Sexpr{round(table$adj.r.squared*100,2)} percent of the adjusted variance. The coefficents
indicate that when the weight of the vehicle increases by 1,000 lbs, the mpg decreases 
by \Sexpr{round(-t[2,1],3)} for cars with automatic transmissions, and decreases 
by \Sexpr{round(-t[3,1],3)} for cars with manual transmissions. When the quarter-mile 
performance time increases by 1 second, the mpg increases \Sexpr{round(t[4,1],3)} for cars 
with automatic transmissions and \Sexpr{round(t[5,1],3)} for cars with manual transmissions. 
This implies that if the car has slower acceleration speeds, other things held constant, cars 
with manual transmissions have larger mpg values. The conclusion of this analysis in one 
sentence is that the mpg variable is largely determined by the relationship between weight 
and accelaration in combination with transmission type.

